{"cursor":"8461","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n\nIn social anthropology, 'matrilocal residence' or 'matrilocality' (also\n'uxorilocal residence' or 'uxorilocality') is a term referring to the societal\nsystem in which a married couple resides with or near the wife's parents, thus\nthe female offspring of a mother remain living in (or near) the mother's house,\nthereby forming large clan-families, typically consisting of three or four\ngenerations living in the same place.\n","linknr":422,"url":"Matrilocality","recorded":1362899074,"links":29,"instances":["tribe"],"pdf":["http://eclectic.ss.uci.edu/~drwhite/worldcul/Korotayev.pdf"],"categories":["Marriage","Sociobiology","Cultural anthropology","Matriarchy"],"headings":["Description","List of matrilocal societies","References","Bibliography","See also"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/f2/Edit-clear.svg/40px-Edit-clear.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a4/Text_document_with_red_question_mark.svg/40px-Text_document_with_red_question_mark.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/41/Woman-power_emblem.svg/17px-Woman-power_emblem.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["garo","tribe"]],"members":["garo"],"related":["Social_anthropology","Society","Mother","House","Clan","Generation","Marriage","Husband","Wife","Child","Matrilineal","Cousin","Property","Inheritance","Horticulture","Ngazidja","Ancient_Pueblo_Peoples","Chaco_Canyon","Nair","Kerala","South_India","Mosuo","Yunnan","Sichuan","China","Siraya_people","Taiwan","Minangkabau_people","Sumatra","Amazonia","Brideservice","Urarina","Peru","Mainland_China","Government_of_the_People's_Republic_of_China","Sex_ratio","Sex-selective_abortion_and_infanticide","Abandonment","Patrilocal_res